<font color="#FF0000">RESPONSE TO NURSE RATCHET</font><br>
<tt>Mon Jan 20 17:19:42 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Dr. Barry Spatz again demonstrates his ignorance by asumming that you are a woman, irregardless that males have served in this noble proffesion for many, many years.  Sorry, Barry, but you found one of my &quot;buttons&quot;.<br>
In spite of what you have stated, Dr. Spatz has contributed some insights represenative of his camp/side of the fence.  The problem is that he has said these things long ago and not much new has surfaced since.  It's a shame, but, I agree that he is a troller just wanting to do battle; that his purpose seems that he wants everyone to capitulate to his views.<br><br>
What is a greater crime is that interest seems to be waning at this dialog site and when that happens, POV will pull the plug on this project.  It costs money to keep this going.  The constants firefights just tire, annoy and disgusts people, turns them off.<br><br>
It would be a shame because, while having been on the net a considerable time, it has been as a voyeur only.  Here @ this site, I have established communications via e-mail with four individuals that I met at this site, and have posted two postings on other threads.  All firsts for me.<br><br>
Let me take another risk.  It was mentioned that there were more than two camps that people could aligned themselves to other than those for the war and those against.  The reason I went into the army and, eventually, to Nam had absolutely nothing with politics.  I went to get out of a bad situation where I lived.  Nothing more. The anti-war movement was young, but growing, but still here in Hawaii, I viewed it as far removed from me.  Once I was in country, I did not want to return for two reasons.  The situation where I lived had not changed and I did not want to abandon my unit.  When I did return, the experience left much to be desired.  It only took me one day to learned that I needed to burn my class-A's and never to mentioned that I was a vet of any kind, irregardless of my MOS.  I bunkered myself in to survive.  That is the key word here-Survival. A mentality that many of us grew up with and was reinforced by our military experiences. Being demonstrative to political views was a luxury not affordable to all, no matter how you felt about the war.<br>
I admit that I had a tunnel vision, that I was solely focused on my own needs, but that narrow focus was a tool necessary to function in my role as a medic.  My job/purpose in life was to keep my men from dying.  I came home with this narrow focus and transfered it to my role as a paramedic, until, like Dr. Spatz, I burned out in 1980.  Having to lose one's purpose in life is rather a traumatic event, so my heart goes out to Dr. Spatz.  I could not except that, thus I &quot;expanded&quot; that role by working with kids with behavioral problems, then with kids with a history of sexual/physical abuse.  In 1989, I had to come to the realization, that the &quot;medic&quot; was dead.  Not since, have I worked in that capacity.<br>
One of those that I communicate with is a woman whose parents were activists during the war.  Through her, it has been an honour getting to know them, what they went through and how they felt in their roles while I was in Nam playing my role.<br>
How about you, Nurse Ratchet?  It is obvious that you followed the conversation on this thread.  I am very much interested in your views.  Unlike Dr. Spatz, I have admiration and respect for those who have contributed to this dialog no matter the views expressed, as long as it stays on the topic, is civilize, AND WE CAN AGREE TO DISAGREE!<br>
I have absolutely no problems with you or others keeping your idenityor e-mail address to yourself.
